<Author>Mgz
<Content>Elegant, attentive service, truly worthwhile visit As an alternative to spending days in the kitchen cooking a huge holiday dinner, we spent 2 nights over Christmas at Dallas' new Ritz Carlton. It was time well spent, one of the most satisfying lodging experiences I've ever had at a very competitive rate for such a property. Comments follow; feel free to email with questions.LOCATIONOn the south end of McKinney Ave, this hotel is directly adjacent to Crescent Court, and a short walk to numerous bars, cafes, shops and restaurants along McKinney Ave. The free trolley also runs in front of the hotel. I walked one night to/from Idle Rich, a great Irish bar, about an 8-10 minute walk. It's a great location.ROOMWe reserved a junior suite at a special bb rate, and were bumped up to a deluxe suite, a very welcome Christmas present.The king bed was very comfortable, part of the trend toward ultra-plush bedding at the better hotels. The bathroom was large, with a deep soak tub and separate shower. My favorite feature, which will now haunt my wife until we get it, was a TV embedded in the mirror above the sinks. Can you say perfect bathroom?The TVs had a Bose sound system, a nice touch. All in all, the room was clean, comfortable, well kept, and as good as we could have wanted.LOBBYNever one to pick a hotel on the lobby - I mean, how important is it, really? - I was impressed with the uncluttered elegance and spaciousness that surrounds once you go through the front door. I've been to a couple of Ritz Carltons, and they always seem to have a number of beautiful paintings and sculptures. It's elegant without being stuffy or unapproachable. DININGWe had breakfast and lunch at Fearings, the relatively new restaurant by Dean Fearing, formerly the focal point of The Mansion At Turtle Creek (where we also dined, see other review). Breakfast was delicious. Eggs Benedict were poached perfectly. The hollandaise was silky and light. The breakfast potatoes, normally the part I avoid due to grease, were so very good. Potatoes, bell and red peppers, onion, butter, all balanced and addictive. The coffee was rich and chewy, just perfect. And service, which I'll speak more to later, was spot on.Lunch was simple, and clearly from the southwestern libraries of Fearing. We had lobster nachos - simple but delicious, lettuce wedge with quail, and today, the famous tortilla soup and braised pork ribs. All were well presented, served with elegance and timeliness, and perfectly seasoned. We did not have dinner there, but I expect it was on par with the best dining in Dallas.Try the gelato in the lobby shop - very smooth, rich but not overly heavy, it was a good copy of an Italian favorite.FYI, the bed and breakfast rate includes a $57 credit at the restaurant.SERVICERoom, food, and everything else doesn't count at all without tremendous service. The Ritz Carlton never fell short in this crucial area. From arrival to check-in, from dining to check-out, service was impeccable. Consistently attentive without being overbearing, we felt so welcome and comfortable every day.I encourage folks to ask questions about the menu at Fearings. You learn a great deal about food from exploring menus. My daughter had braised ribs at three different places this week, and is now a knowledgable connoisseur of braising. Guess what Dad has to cook soon! All service folks treated my daughter with respect, impressing me immensely. A special thanks to Aubrey in the bar and Rob at concierge who were most attentive and generous. They helped make this a special Christmas. All the doormen and housekeeping were equally gracious.CONS:Really, none to speak of. My daughter wanted to swim in the heated outdoor pool, and unfortunately the heater was not working, so that disappointed. Otherwise, all was well.This hotel is an excellent choice for people looking for an elegant, comfortable oasis in a great neighborhood, and I highly recommend it. 
