<Author>eyerep74
<Content>Don't bother.....they don't! I stayed at this hotel for 2 nights for my wedding weekend. I found the service at this hotel to run hot and cold.  Upon arriving at the hotel I was graciously greeted by the valets and promptly received help with my bags.  At check-in a very helpful gentlemen at the desk made the process painless. I have to say that I was shocked to find out that Wi-Fi is $9.95 a night! C'mon, I just spent a night at a Hampton Inn in San Angelo and they have it FREE! It's a little insulting to charge over $400.00 a night and have to pay for a service that every hotel on the planet provides free of charge.  Once I was in my room on the Club Level I was annoyed to realize that the room I was given was nothing like the Club Level room photos shown on their website. They make it look like you're getting a 2 room suite with a living room and bedroom with 2 tv's etc. I got a typical hotel room and a nicely sized bathroom and that's it. Nothing to scream about. I've stayed in nicer. And I too found hair (not mine) all over the bathroom floor and was not pleased with the cleanliness of the room in general.  I have to admit that the Club Level is worth it for access to the Club. It's wonderful for light snacks and it's a beautiful quiet space to just sit in and relax.  I didn't sleep for the 2 nights I was there because the bed in my room was as hard as a rock and the stupid feather pillows flatten like pancakes in about 10 minutes offering no neck support.  For my wedding transportation, I booked a package back in Feb. that included the use of a Mercedes. Two months before my wedding I called the hotel to confirm and was told that the package I had already reserved and paid for was no longer available. I was never contacted by the hotel to alert me of this potentially disasterous mishap. The hotel was nice enough to accomadate me by offering their house car (a very nice Bentley) and a driver which was more than acceptable to me. The day before the wedding I went to the check-in desk to confirm the times the driver needed to take us and pick us up. I was lucky enough to be helped once again by the nice gentlemen that had checked me in earlier. He was very polite and was getting ready to write down the times when out of nowhere the very snotty girl working with him decided to pipe in to rudely tell me that they already knew what time and they were aware of it. I then asked if I would be allowed to bring my photographer into the hotel to take photos and also asked if there would be a rooftop patio on the property that I would be able to access. The nice man said they didn't have a patio, but I might want to check out the pool on the second floor and the girl decided to pipe in again with something about how it probably wasn't what I was looking for. I don't know who she was or why she decided to join in on the conversation that he was handling beautifully, but in my opinion she is not fit for any kind of customer service position anywhere. There is one thing that is kind of confusing about this hotel. There are residences within the property, but no signs letting hotel guests which areas are accessible to them and which areas are not. I had 2 situations where I accidentally roamed into the residential side and the first time I was treated with absolute professionalism and the second time I was treated like I had committed the biggest crime in the world. I was again rudely told that their residents pay a lot of money to live there and deserve to have their private space protected. Which I agree with completely. Put up some signs then! Provide outdoor seating for hotel guests like you do for your residents and maybe hotel guests won't roam the property for a place to sit down! And nevermind the fact that I'm spending over $1,000.00 for my stay!  To sum it up, I wasn't impressed with this hotel at all. I would stay at a Westin for the Heavenly bed alone. The hardest working people at this hotel are the valets and the nice guy with the little glasses at the front desk. That's it. Customer service as a whole has some serious renovating to do. I don't know, maybe I expected way too much. It's kind of like shopping at Saks and paying $100.00 for a t-shirt and finding the same shirt at Marshall's the next day for half price. You kind of feel like a jerk for buying into the hype. 
